<Text>I've never been one to leave reviews online but I had to share my experience with my visit to Dr. Cheung's office.

To start, when I first called in to make an appointment I was treated very kindly and professionally by Jocelyn. Before calling SCOMSA, I called several other oral surgeons in the area and lot of the other places will just take your info and make an appointment without asking you questions about your current dental health or checking if your visit will be covered by insurance (which is kind of devious). Jocelyn took down all of my info and checked to ensure that my visit would be covered by my insurance and noted my current dental health while giving me the option to come in for a consultation or a consultation straight to surgery. I booked my appointment and came in the following day for my consultation.

Before arriving I called in to let them know I was outside so they could prepare for my visit and ensure that there was proper hygiene in the facility to protect their staff & I from any possible COVID 19 infection. They took my temperature and got me in for X-rays very quickly to ensure I would have a quick consultation. With that said though, there was no rush to get me in & out.

After getting my X-ray, Dr. Cheung greeted me and we got to chatting about what I do and had a great conversation about how we're both interested in Bitcoin. Dr. Cheung went over my X-rays with me and made me feel right at home and explained everything to me regarding my current dental health and the needs for the procedure, mentioning how he has done the same procedure on several of his own kids and would treat me with the same level of respect & kindness throughout my experience. He also informed me of all the risks and possible complications that come with surgery but ensured me of his upmost concern for safety and promised that everything would go safe & smoothly. With that I booked my appointment for my surgery for the following Monday.

The Day of my surgery I was greeted with the same experience for the quick and clean entry into the facility. Immediately I was greeted by Dr. Cheung's assistant for the surgery in which we chatted about the procedure and other things related to my family. Initially I was very nervous but after the chat I felt at ease thanks to the comforting conversations we had before the surgery began. Dr. Cheung then came in with another assistant and ran through the procedure one last time before we began, in which he reassured my confidence in him and his team. We had a quick laugh about talking about Bitcoin and before I knew it, I was quickly anesthetized and came to towards the end of the procedure, to the point where I thought they hadn't done the left side of my mouth and I asked them if they were moving onto the left side as they were finishing the right, but they informed me I was done! As I was getting ready to leave they gave me all of the prescription drugs I would need so I wouldn't have to visit a pharmacy and they gave me all the instructions to properly recover.

It's been 2 days since my surgery and I'm feeling great! My recovery is happening very quickly and I feel some soreness but it's very easy to deal with. After witnessing family & friends endure pain and discomfort for days after their wisdom teeth removals (from other oral surgeons) I was nervous for my recovery, but it has been a breeze. Along with the drugs and instructions, Dr. Cheung also provided a nice headband that holds ice pouches that has really helped with the swelling and discomfort in my face and it's been working wonders.

All & all, if you're looking for a place to get any kind of oral surgery, I highly recommend SCOMSA and Dr. Cheung. Their staff is very friendly and professional and made me feel more than confident in their capabilities.

Fun Fact: Dr. Cheung is a Bitcoin advocate like me, and he is accepting Bitcoin as my form of payment for the surgery!! Not sure there are many other doctors around that accept Bitcoin so this was also super cool!</Text><Pics>None</Pics><response>None< /response>< gmapID>

<rate>1< /rate>< Review>
Longino is an agent for American Income Life Insurance Co.  So why wasn't I told that when they emailed me for an interview?  Why did I stand outside of their suite, which is in a very nice building, wondering why it didn't say Longino? It said American Income Life for suite 350. Why was I told the job is offering benefits to union and credit union members.  Why wasn't I told the job is 100% commission? The one answer to those questions is YOU PROBABLY WOULDN'T ACCEPT THE INTERVIEW OPPORTUNITY.  This is a scam to get you to become a Life Insurance Agent. You have to pay for the pre-course, the state exam and the licensing, which is several hundred dollars, all before you receive a dime in compensation. If they have to present what I consider deceptive information to get me to come to what I was told was going to be an interview with the Regional Manager, then how can I believe anything they tell me after that?  Sure you can sell to union & credit union members but you will be selling to everyone that is over 18, has a pulse and wants Life Insurance. Your an agent.</Review>

I have never had to use Urgent Care before and with COVID-19 I wanted to chose a place that looked clean and would give me a low risk of contracting the virus. This place is located next to the Acura LG dealership which is where I purchased my car and get my car serviced so I was very familiar with the area and felt comfortable going to this location.

< Review>
If you are looking for entertainment or wedding venue, it's fantastic. If you are looking for social not beneficial gatherings definitely good. But if you are building business, looking for network or looking for good connections save your money and look for other business oriented club .
Most members are small biz, real estate agents, insurance agents etc.

The Silicon valley Capital Club is at the top floor of the Night Ridder building in DTSJ, the place is clean and the waiters/staff are professional, the views from deck look great.</Review>

<Text>This is a new restaurant in Brentwood. They have Japanese and Chinese food. We tried the chef's choice 12 piece sashimi, the Heart Attack, honey walnut prawns, spider roll and a variety of other food. The Heart Attack is a jalapeno stuffed with cream cheese and crab then deep fried. If a jalapeno popper is a burger, this is a perfectly cooked steak. I definitely recommend trying this. All the sushi and sashimi were prepared perfectly. Great presentation and all the dishes are full of flavor. I don't live close to Brentwood, but would definitely go back to this place again.<//Text>< userid>

< Text>
I needed to add my mom to my plan, and transfer her over from another carrier. I recently saw that this store is open, and decided to come here instead of waiting in a line at the always busy Slatten Ranch location. The staff here is AMAZING! They are knowledgeable, professional, and so friendly. We had the pleasure to work with Khalil, Yessenia,  Melissa, and Alex. T-mobile is so lucky to have this awesome group representing them. We had some issues transferring from her previous carrier (*cough*Sprint*cough*), but all of these employees helped take care of us, and made sure that we got the right plan for us (my grandfathered plan), with the right phone for her needs. Not only that, but while they were working on getting us up and running, they were talking to us, and I could tell that they genuinely cared. We left with hugs all around! I will be back to this location for any of my future T-mobile needs. Thanks guys!< /Text>

< Review>
I was thrilled to discover a new Japanese restaurant in Brentwood.  However, after ordering the Katsu chicken and vegetable tempura, we may not be returning.

The place was packed full on a Friday evening.  We had to wait about 20 minutes to get a table.  No biggie.

They have a counter along one wall, but it was loosely hanging on and tilted.  Definitely not a stable place to eat.  They need to get rid of that thing.  It looks bad.  Also, they have what looks like a beautiful water fountain behind the check-in counter.  But, this was bone dry, dirty, and just an eyesore to look at wh2n you first walk in.

The chicken katsu was a horrible piece of chicken.  Definitely not a nice clean piece of white meat breast.  50% of the piece was full of fat and gristle, and the other 50% was flavorless cheap dark meat.  This was a huge disappointment.  I have had awesome chicken katsu breasts in the past, but this place does not care to give their customers a nice choice piece of meat.

We might give this place one more try, to see if this was just an unfortunate anomaly.  Not sure.  That chicken was really gross.

Have a little more pride in the food you serve and give your customers a better piece of meat.<//Review>

< Review>
So regretful that I chose this salon. I went in with a clear explanation of the color I wanted,  and even showed Ana Lisa several photos of my platinum hair color on MY head. I stressed that my biggest concern was that she get the right color. Well, not only did it turn out so bad,  I ended up with pinkish purplish hair!!  She never said a word when she took off the foils, just turned my chair away from the mirror and proceeded to blow it out, knowing full well what a disaster it was!  When I turned my head to look,  I was shocked!  To think I was afraid of a brassy color.  This was pink hair!!  And upon further inspection I even found patches of purple and lavender!  I just don't get it. My previous hairdresser had no problem at all with my hair. I question how much experience this girl even has with color, or whether or not she's even licensed!  I'm also very disappointed with the owner,  Anna.  I initially consulted with her,  and when I realized she was way out of my price range, she referred me to Ana Lisa.  The thing is,  I expressed to Anna as well, that my biggest concern was the color.  Why refer me to someone who clearly has little experience in color??  So upset and disappointed.   To add insult to injury? Instead of accepting responsibility and apologizing, she tried to blame me and our consultation!  Girl,  I showed you actual photos!!  And FYI, my previous highlights had already grown out, so she couldn't even blame it on that.  To the receptionists credit,  she was much more apologetic and offered to have it fixed at another time,  however,  I'm  absolutely petrified to go back.  I have pics, but I guess this site doesn't allow you to post pics. You can catch them on Yelp.

Talk about a back-handed apology!  Why bother if you are putting it that way and slandering me? <Rating>4< /Rating>< review>
I go to Lowe's pretty often. Mostly, because it is so close. It does seem that you are usually on your own if you are having trouble finding something. But, the employees that help are always very nice. My guess is, they minimize the staff to keep the costs down. I did have Lowe's put a fence in my back yard. The person that gave me a quote also told me that a large limb on a tree would not have to be cut if I put a 6 foot fence in instead of a five foot fence. Yeah, I lost a major limb in the tree. They also mis-measured the spacing for the fence posts, so they had to put an extra post in, which looks pretty strange. I am guessing that fence installation gets contracted out. The two that did my fence seemed pretty young. I also had Lowe's install my laminate floor in my house. They did a pretty decent job on that. Well, who ever they contracted to do it, that is.< /review>

<Name>Garrett Lewis</Name><time>1522881809737</time><rate>1</rate>< Review>
